<h3>PhilPapers Resources</h3>
<p>These will sometimes have an article in the archive (look for "Download from Archive"). Otherwise there will be links to the paper under "External Links". Sometimes all the links will be paywalled - but in every case if you are on a university computer, or if you have logged into the university network from an off-site computer, you should have access.</p>
<p><strong>None of these articles require you to pay; at worst they require a password to show that you have UM library privileges.</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Simon M. Huttegger, Justin P. Bruner &amp; Kevin J. S. Zollman, <a href="https://philpapers.org/rec/HUTTHP-2">The Handicap Principle Is an Artifact</a></li>
<li>Christian List &amp; Philip Pettit, <a href="https://philpapers.org/rec/LISASO-3">Aggregating sets of judgments: An impossibility result</a></li>
<li>Jeffrey Sanford Russell, John Hawthorne &amp; Lara Buchak, <a href="https://philpapers.org/rec/RUSG">Groupthink</a></li>
<li>Julia Staffel, <a href="https://philpapers.org/rec/STADAE-4">Disagreement and Epistemic Utility-Based Compromise</a></li>
<li>Margaret Gilbert, <a href="https://philpapers.org/rec/GILWTA">Walking Together: A Paradigmatic Social Phenomenon</a></li>
<li>Michael E. Bratman, <a href="https://philpapers.org/rec/BRASCA">Shared cooperative activity</a></li>
<li>Michael E. Bratman, <a href="https://philpapers.org/rec/BRASI">Shared Intention</a></li>
<li>Jennifer Lackey, <a href="https://philpapers.org/rec/LACSEK">Socially extended knowledge</a></li>
<li>Neil Levy &amp; Mark Alfano, <a href="https://philpapers.org/rec/LEVKFV">Knowledge From Vice: Deeply Social Epistemology</a></li>
<li>Alexander Bird, <a href="https://philpapers.org/rec/BIRSKT">Social knowing: The social sense of 'scientific knowledge'</a></li>
<li>Jennifer Lackey, <a href="https://philpapers.org/rec/LACWIJ">What Is Justified Group Belief</a></li>
</ul>
<h3>Papers on JSTOR</h3>
<p>These will definitely require you to be on a University computer, or have setup your home computer for offsite access.&nbsp;<strong>Again, none of these require payment of any kind as long as you have a UM account</strong>.</p>
<ul>
<li>Michael Spence, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/1882010?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents">Job Market Signaling</a></li>
<li>Amartya Sen, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/1829633?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents">The Impossibility of a Paretian Liberal</a></li>
<li>Amartya Sen, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/117024?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents">The Possibility of Social Choice</a></li>
</ul>
